<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910306-0109</DOCNO><DOCID>910306-0109.</DOCID><HL>   Mesa to Sell Conoco   Gas, Coal Properties   Valued at $165 Million</HL><DATE>03/06/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7</SO><CO>   MLP DD SGO</CO><IN>OIL, SECONDARY (OIS)PETROLEUM (PET)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)EARNINGS (ERN)</IN><LP>   DALLAS -- Mesa Limited Partnership said it signed a letterof intent to sell oil, natural gas and coal properties for$165 million to Conoco Inc.   The sale, when coupled with two other planned propertysales, will help Mesa cut by almost half its $900 million inbank debt. The company has been trying to sell assets, orraise new funds, for about a year to avoid a potentialliquidity problem next year.</LP><TEXT>   The oil and natural gas concern, which is led by T. BoonePickens Jr., said it will sell Conoco its properties in theSan Juan Basin in northwestern New Mexico and southwesternColorado. The sale is expected to close in April. Conoco is aunit of E.I. du Pont de Nemours andamp; Co.   Earlier this month, Mesa sold $74 million in properties.And it plans to complete a $201 million sale to SeagullEnergy Corp. of Houston in the next few weeks.   Altogether, Mesa is selling about 17% of its oil andnatural gas reserves, including about 6% in the Conocotransaction. After the sales are completed, about 93% of itsproperties will be located in the Hugoton Field of Kansas andthe West Panhandle Field of Texas.   As part of its debt-refinancing plan, the company will usethe Hugoton Field properties to secure $616 million in newprivately placed debt that will help it retire the rest ofits bank debt and better match its debt maturities withproduction of its natural gas reserves. The new debt offeringis expected to be completed by the end of the month.   Mesa also said it had a fourth-quarter net loss of $136.6million, or $1.01 a share, largely because of a $75.7 millionloss on the sale of oil and gas properties and a $34.3million loss on securities transactions. In the year-earlierperiod, the company had a net loss of $42.7 million, or 25cents a share. The year-ago results included a $2 milliongain from property sales and a $3.3 million securities loss.   Revenue for the recent quarter rose 28% to $97.1 millionfrom $75.8 million.</TEXT></DOC>